    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nPriori to 0.11, `DiagnosticUnnecessary` has priority over `DiagnosticUnderlineWarn`. This is intended because `unnecessary` is a sub diagnostic tag. After 0.12, `DiagnosticUnderlineWarn` has priority instead, which disallows overriding highlight style for `DiagnosticUnnecessary`.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nEnable LSP\n```lua\nvim.diagnostic.enable()\nvim.diagnostic.config({ underline = true })\nvim.cmd.hi(\"DiagnosticUnderlineWarn ctermfg=231 ctermbg=136 guifg=#ffffff guibg=#c09e3f\")\nvim.cmd.hi(\"DiagnosticUnnecessary ctermfg=245 guifg=#8a8a8a\")\n```\nOpen any code where there is an unused variable\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe unused variable should be grey., but instead, it is yellow.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.12.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nn/a\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 26.4\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nghostty NVIM v0.12.0\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-ghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Bisected to 2767eac320ef3f422236cbc8ce2228b02e11bd31 (#36590). It seems the scenario where the \"main\" hl-group also has a fg color wasn't handled. I think `DiagnosticUnnecessary` should have higher priority here, it's odd that it isn't, given that it applies later in the loop.",
